-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">1. Consider Your Workout</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1659008080564" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1659008080564" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Before looking at the shoe characteristics, consider the type of workout or sport you’ll be performing regularly. If your training mainly consists of weight lifting, go for a shoe with a bigger heel lift that offers extra support in the midsole area. If your focus is cross training, you want a shoe with a flatter heel that offers excellent breathability. If you plan to do a combination of both, a shoe that has a mild heel lit and <a href="https://austinpublishinggroup.com/textile-engineering/fulltext/arte-v8-id1081.pdf" class="" target="_blank">materials</a> offering good breathability might be the best option.</p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685574196774" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1685574196774"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">2. Shoe Materials</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1659008080570" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1659008080570" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>When considering shoe materials, you can split them into three different sections - the upper, midsole, and bottom. Training shoes are typically made of breathable mesh upper materials that allow moisture to escape whilst offering excellent comfort. If you need extra ankle support, check the upper shoe height to see if they are suitable. In terms of the midsole, some shoes have different cushioning materials that react to your movement pattern and cushioning to support lateral movements. The shoe sole should offer good traction and be made from durable rubber material that can withstand repeated impact in outdoor environments.</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1687474517583" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1687474517583" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/60e16f37-6bb3-493c-b624-9f0dd789c2a8/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/lifting-exercise.jpg" alt="lifting exercise" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="lifting exercise" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1689112963647" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1689112963647"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">3. Heel Shape and Support</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1689112975286" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1689112975286" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>A wide, flared-out heel will provide a more <a href="https://pilotfeasibilitystudies.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s40814-022-01157-2" class="" target="_blank">stable lifting base</a> whilst a narrow heel offers less stability but supports a wider range of dynamic lifting movements. Choose the heel shape and size that supports your preferred lifestyle.</p><p>Whilst most training shoes have a flat heel, some offer an elevated heel height to support force generation and improve mobility and <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27096286/" class="" target="_blank">performance</a>. Check the heel height and consider the main training movements you'll be doing.</p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1659008080577" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1659008080577" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass="" data-layout-lg="12" data-layout-md="12" data-layout-sm="12" data-layout-xs="12"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1658828961229" data-id="1658828961229"><div data-label="Liquid" data-key="liquid" data-atomgroup="module" id="m-1685568799611" class="module-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-liquid" data-ver="1.1" data-id="1685568799611" data-name="Right click on this, and choose Edit Code."><div class="module gf_module- gf_module--lg gf_module--md gf_module--sm gf_module--xs {{extraClass}}"><script type="application/ld+json">{"@context": "https://schema.org","@type": "FAQPage","mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question","name": "What Are the Best Nike Trainers to Wear for General Lifestyle Activities?","acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer","text": "Sneakers for general lifestyle activities should be comfortable to wear and allow unrestricted movement. The best pair of Nike trainers should be based on your budget, preference, and previous trainer use. Look for shoes with a flat heel, supportive midsole, and breathable upper."}},{"@type": "Question","name": "Which Pair of Nike Shoes Are the Best for the Gym?